defaultUK
default jurisdiction.
default 
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: Having a sponsor based in the 
defaultUK
default actually is of real benefit in that circumstance because, on a day-to-day basis, most of our dialogue in relation to an issuer actually in fact is with the sponsor.
default 
defaultHaving a sponsor firm that has a close relationship with the issuer that it is representing is actually helpful for us in terms of ensuring that the issuer complies with the regime.
default 
defaultRegarding the financing aspect, which you have talked about, a sponsor does need to be paid somehow, and having the issuer pay for it would be no different from having the issuer pay for the audit.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ151 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Walker:default Can I just ask what legal liability the sponsor has for the veracity of the listing particulars and the details that they publish?
default 
defaultAre they legally liable for telling the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: They are certainly liable to us under our regimes.
default 
defaultIn other words, as I was mentioning a few moments ago, if sponsor confirmations turn out to have been inaccurate or produced in a sloppy way, that would bring them under the purview of our discipline.
default 
defaultI must admit I do not know whether they are able to be pursued through the courts by a third party.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ152 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Walker:default There is also the question not only of accuracy but of inclusivity— including all the facts rather than just stating some which are true.
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: Yes
default.
default The main document that issuers use to come to market is the prospectus.
default 
defaultThe directors of the company take responsibility for the prospectus and they are liable for its contents.
default 
defaultIf there is something that is misleading in a prospectus, then third parties do have the ability to take the directors to court for redress in that respect.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ153 default&#xa0; 
defaultAnn defaultMcKechindefault:default Mr Lawton, there was an intriguing remark in your written evidence.
default 
defaultYou said, “Our review of an application for listing focuses on ensuring the applicant meets the admission criteria and is therefore eligible for listing.
default 
defaultWe do not consider whether it is suitable for listing.”
default 
defaultI think most people would find that rather surprising, so why not?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: Those two terms are perhaps terms of art in the listing space.
default 
defaultWhat I am trying to say there is that the criteria for admission to the List are objective and objectively verifiable.
default 
defaultWhat we are not doing is making any comment on a company’s business model.
default 
defaultFor example, if an issuer came to us saying, “We’re a widget
default&#x2011;
defaultmaker
default,” we make no comments on whether widget
default&#x2011;
defaultmaking
default is a good business to be in, nor are we making any comment, as we were saying in response to Mr Binley, about whether this is an investment that will make money for investors.
default 
defaultThe focus of our regime is to ensure that issuers make accurate disclosures about themselves in order to enable investors to take a view about whether they want to consider it as an investable proposition.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ154 default&#xa0; 
defaultAnn defaultMcKechindefault:default At present, no one actually makes that decision about whether they are suitable for listing in the sense that you have interpreted it.
default 
