defaultQ158 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Could you just make clear if there have been any examples where you have said that an applicant company does meet all the criteria from a financial point of view and then the listing authorities turn them down?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: We do have that power in practice.
defaultChair:default No, I am asking if it has happened.
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: It has happened but, in practice, what tends to happen is that applicants withdraw before we make a final determination.
default 
defaultWhen they take a view that we are likely to turn that application down, typically they withdraw their application.
defaultChair:default I am talking about you accepting their application or saying that it meets the appropriate criteria, but the 
defaultUK
default listing authority then deciding to turn it down.
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: In that circumstance, we would say it had not met the criteria, so actually the two questions are the same question.
default 
defaultGoing back to what we talked about, if people are particularly interested, for example, in this concern about financial crime, a statutory objective of ours i
defaults
default to protect and enhance the integrity of the 
defaultUK
default financial system.
default 
defaultThe legislation defines that in part as taking into account the use of the financial system to further financial crime, so that becomes part of our overall assessment.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ159 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default I understand that it is normal for a company being listed to have over 25% of its shares available for the open market.
default 
defaultNow, in some cases, including ENRC, they have been listed without having that requirement.
default 
defaultCan you explain why an exception was made for companies like this?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: The basic rule is that there need to be sufficient shares in public hands for there to be a liquid secondary market, so that the trading of the shares subsequently works on a satisfactory basis.
default 
defaultThe European listing legislation sets 25% as the basic indicator of sufficient liquidity in the secondary market, but it does give us the ability to have a lower threshold where we are satisfied that there are sufficient shares in public hands for there to be sufficient liquidity.
default 
defaultIn a small number of cases with very large companies, we have assessed that that liquidity criterion would be satisfied with free floats of somewhat less than 25%.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ160 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default The logic of what you have just said would seem to imply that, if a company is of a certain size, there are likely to be enough shares on the free market not to apply that 25% criterion.
default 
defaultIs that a rough and ready rule?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: Yes, but it only happens relatively rarely.
default 
defaultAnother aspect to think about is that, for very large companies coming to market for the first time, there can often be a 
defaultcapacity question.
default 
defaultThe market can only absorb a certain amount of new capital raising at any one point.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ161 default&#xa0; 
