defaultDavid Lawtondefault: They would have to satisfy the capital markets rules in each jurisdiction in which they access capital markets, so all of them.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ170 default&#xa0; 
defaultCaroline defaultDinenagedefault:default If the rules differ or go off in different directions, would they abide differently in different countries?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: Yes.
default 
defaultTypically, the rules would not be conflicting; they would be in layers.
default 
defaultA company, as a matter of practice, would satisfy the capital markets rules of the most stringent jurisdiction.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ171 default&#xa0; 
defaultCaroline defaultDinenagedefault:default Quickly, because I know you have already touched on this, could you just outline what the difference is between a primary and a secondary listing, please?
defaultDavid Lawtondefault: Secondary listing was the term that we used to use when companies wanted a second listing, i.e. non
default&#x2011;
defaultUK companies.
default 
defaultWe changed the regime about five years or so ago and opened up that category to 
defaultUK
default companies and renamed it standard listing.
default 
defaultA standard listing is one that embodies the European legislative criteria in relation to prospectuses, disclosures and so on.
default 
defaultA premium listing adds some additional requirements on top of that.
default 
defaultFor the issuer, there is a need to have a three
default&#x2011;
defaultyear track record, to be able to say that you have enough working capital to survive at least 12
default&#xa0;
defaultmonths of activity, and you also have to appoint a sponsor.
default 
defaultOn an ongoing basis, a premium
default&#x2011;
defaultlisted
default issuer also has to offer shareholders additional rights to have votes over important transactions such as major acquisitions or transactions with related parties.
